Quick summary

Make InfluxDB listen on all interfaces (not just localhost) by using the --http-bind-address option (or the equivalent systemd/env variable). 
docs.influxdata.com
+1

Open/allow TCP port 8086 on the host firewall (or the port you choose). 
docs.influxdata.com

Restart InfluxDB and verify from a remote machine.

Step-by-step (Linux systemd install)

Check current listener (run on the InfluxDB host)

sudo ss -tlnp | grep 8086
# or
sudo netstat -tlnp | grep 8086


If it shows 127.0.0.1:8086 then Influx binds only to localhost.

Tell influxd to bind to all interfaces
Edit the systemd environment file /etc/default/influxdb2 (or the systemd unit drop-in for your distro) and add the http bind argument. Example (create/update /etc/default/influxdb2):

sudo tee /etc/default/influxdb2 >/dev/null <<'EOF'
ARG1="--http-bind-address :8086"
EOF


This passes --http-bind-address :8086 to influxd, which binds the HTTP API/UI to all interfaces (equivalent to 0.0.0.0:8086). You can also use 0.0.0.0:8086 explicitly. 
docs.influxdata.com
+1

Alternative: if you start influxd manually, run:

influxd --http-bind-address :8086


Restart InfluxDB

sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl restart influxdb
sudo systemctl status influxdb --no-pager


Open the port in the firewall (example for Ubuntu with ufw)

sudo ufw allow 8086/tcp
sudo ufw status


Or with iptables/firewalld use the equivalent command for your distro. (Port 8086 is the InfluxDB HTTP/API default.) 
docs.influxdata.com

If running in Docker: map the port when starting:

docker run -p 8086:8086 influxdb:2.0


(If already running, recreate the container with -p 8086:8086.) 
gallery.ecr.aws

Verify from another PC on the LAN

From a remote machine (replace HOST_IP with your InfluxDB host IP):

curl -v http://HOST_IP:8086/health
# expected: JSON status / http 200 if reachable


Or open http://HOST_IP:8086 in a browser to reach the UI.

Troubleshooting checklist

If ss/netstat still shows 127.0.0.1:8086, check how the service is started — your systemd unit might ignore /etc/default/influxdb2. Inspect the unit file:

systemctl cat influxdb


If the port is blocked: re-check host firewall and any network-level firewall or router rules.

If you’re using a cloud VM, ensure provider security group / network ACL allows port 8086.

Security notes (important)

Exposing InfluxDB to a network means clients could access data or tokens. Keep it limited to your LAN (don’t expose to the public internet) and use strong tokens. 
docs.influxdata.com

Consider putting a reverse proxy in front with TLS & auth, or restrict access by IP using firewall rules.

If you must expose externally, use HTTPS/TLS and strictly control tokens and firewall rules.

